<h2 class="date">Apr 13, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Some Exam 2 Announcements</h3>
<ul>
<li> You are allowed one sheet of notes as well as a simple calculator, just like Exam 1.
<li> The exam focuses on the materials we've covered after the midterm, but you should also expect some questions covering earlier materials.
<li> Topics may include:
<ul>
<li> Semantic representation (especially first order logic)
<li> Compositional semantics (similar to questions in homework 4)
<li> Lexical semantics (WSD, semantic role labeling, word similarity metrics)
<li> Computational discourse (pronomial coreference resolution, textual coherence)
</ul>
</ul>
</div>
<h2 class="date">Apr 9, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Lecture 23</h3>
<p> This lecture introduces computational discourse. In particular, we focused on anaphora resolution. Here are some brief <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/04.09.pdf">notes</a> from class. This lecture corresponds to Chapter 21 of J&M.
</div>

<h2 class="date">Apr 7, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Lecture 22</h3>
<p> In this lecture, we further discussed three relevant tasks in lexical semantics: semantic role labeling, word sense disambiguation, and word similarities. Here are some brief <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/04.07.pdf">notes</a> from the lecture. This lecture corresponds to Chapter 20 of J&M.
</div>

<h2 class="date">Apr 2, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Lecture 21</h3>
<p> In this lecture, we introduced issues concerning lexical
semantics. This corresponds to Chapter 19 of J&M. Here are some brief
<a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/04.02.pdf">notes</a>
from the lecture. 
</div>

<h2 class="date">Mar 31, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Lecture 20</h3>
<p> In this lecture, we traced through several compositional semantics
examples during class. This corresponds to the first half of Chapter
18 from J&M. We also touched on an alternative approach to
syntax-driven semantics, using Combinatory Categorial Grammars
(CCGs). You may be interested in the <a
href="http://yoavartzi.com/tutorial/">tutorial</a> given by Yoav
Artzi at ACL 2013 (I primarily focused on his section 3.2.1, but you
might find the learning part interesting as well).

<h3 class="title">Homework 4</h3>
<p> This assignment is due by 4/7, 11:59pm. It consists of five exercises from the texbook. Here are the <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/hw4.pdf">details</a>.

<b>Edit 4/3:</b> <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/hw4photo.pdf">Here</a> is a version of the assignment with the problem inlined for people who don't have a copy of the book ready. Thanks to Yun Huang for compiling the assignment questions.

</div>
