<h2 class="date">Feb 5, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Lecture 10</h3>
<p> Today we continued our discussions on POS tagging. We introduced a probabilistic model called the Hidden Markov Model, which is useful for many problems, not limited to tagging in NLP. Here are some <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/02.05.pdf">notes</a> corresponding to today's discussions. Please also read Chapter 5 of J\&M.
</div>

<h2 class="date">Feb 3, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Lecture 9</h3>
<p> Today we began talking about tagging problems in NLP. Specifically, we discussed parts-of-speech tagging. We considered a few learning and non-learning approaches for this task. Next, we will look into a specific kind of probabilistic model of the tagging problem in detail (Hidden Markov Model). Here are some <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/02.03.pdf">notes</a> corresponding to today's discussions. Please also read Chapter 5 of J&M.
</div>

<h2 class="date">Jan 29, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
<h3 class="title">Lectures 7, 8</h3>
<p> This week's focus is on smoothing methods for ngram language models. Here are some <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/01.27.pdf">slides</a> that summarize the main concepts. You should also carefully read Chapter 4 of the textbook.
</div>

