<h2 class="date">Jan 22, 2015</h2>
<div class="blogbody">
  <h3 class="title">Lecture 6</h3>
  <p> We continued our discussion on n-gram language models. We framed the problem of developing an n-gram model as a machine learning problem. We talked about how to train the model (with maximum likelihood estimate) and how to evaluate it (using the perplexity/entropy metric for intrinsic evaluation, using LM in an application for an extrinsic evaluation).

  <p> Here are some brief <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/01.22.pdf">notes</a> to highlight our discussion points in class.
  </div>

  <h2 class="date">Jan 20, 2015</h2>
  <div class="blogbody">
    <h3 class="title">Lecture 5</h3>
    <p> We finished up our discussions on using finite state transducers to perform some simple morphological analysis. We've also introduced weighted finite state machines. We talked about how to apply WFSM for the purpose of performing probabilistic language modeling. Here are some <a href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs2731/01.20.pdf">notes</a> from the lecture. This corresponds to Chapter 4 of the textbook.

    <p> People have asked for some FST exercises. Here are some for you to try (Adapted from Anoop Sarkar's notes):
      <ul> 
	<li> rot13 encryption (map each of the 26 alphabet letters to one that is 13 letters ahead of it (mod 26). So "cipher" is rewritten as "pvcure" etc.
	<li> add one in binary: input = Binary(n); output = Binary(n+1)
	<li> Translate from English to "<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pig_Latin">Pig Latin</a>." For example, "Pig Latin is goofy" becomes "Igpay Atinlay isway oofygay."
	</ul>
	
